WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.080
Today, I want to talk about data science organizer burnout.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:14.720
And part of the reason I want to talk about this is that I think this is kind of a common

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:22.120
experience and the more we talk about it with each other, the more we can kind of get better.

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:28.920
So if you feel like you want to share your burnout story, please share it on Slido if

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:30.520
you like.

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:37.520
This is a pretty short talk, so there's plenty of time to kind of share stories and things.

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:39.139
So who am I?

00:00:39.139 --> 00:00:44.400
So I am a community organizer, obviously.

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:47.919
So right now, I co-organize Portland R user group.

00:00:47.919 --> 00:00:54.200
But I've done other organizations, such as the Cascadia R Conference, which is continuing

00:00:54.200 --> 00:00:59.959
its sixth year, which is awesome.

00:00:59.959 --> 00:01:05.199
And when, like I started with a group, like I co-founded called Oregon Health and Science

00:01:05.199 --> 00:01:07.660
University Biodata Club.

00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:09.519
So that's who I am.

00:01:09.519 --> 00:01:13.440
But I spent a lot of time talking with community organizers.

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:18.820
So this is really the collective wisdom of everyone.

00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:20.980
So let's start.

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:24.779
And I was talking with my other fellow speakers.

00:01:24.779 --> 00:01:27.260
It seems like everyone has a COVID story.

00:01:27.260 --> 00:01:28.900
This is my COVID story.

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:31.779
So 2020, COVID happened.

00:01:31.779 --> 00:01:35.940
And it proceeded to make all of us miserable.

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:40.300
It made us all isolated.

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:48.699
And as a result, just me, this is me, but I think a lot of organizers had the same experience.

00:01:49.699 --> 00:01:54.660
And these are all kind of symptoms of burnout, feeling like you're alone, that what you're

00:01:54.660 --> 00:02:02.419
doing is not enough, and what you're doing is not helping people.

00:02:02.419 --> 00:02:09.020
So one thing I will recommend if you're experiencing burnout is start questioning it.

00:02:09.020 --> 00:02:14.940
So that's where I started was basically saying, how can I fight my burnout?

00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:19.820
And more importantly, it felt like organizing was a drain on my energy.

00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:25.880
So I wanted to kind of rethink things and say, how can I get energy from organizing?

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:29.979
And the most important thing, and I think this is kind of part of the moral of this

00:02:29.979 --> 00:02:34.020
talk is, how can others help?

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:40.100
So let's take some time to vision what's possible.

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:43.860
So what if your meetup required less planning from you?

00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:46.100
What if your members pitched in?

00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:48.380
And what if you had support?

00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:54.380
So I'm going to call this a sustainable meetup.

00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:58.759
So if you are an R person, this is the formula.

00:02:58.759 --> 00:03:05.419
So you take your meetup, and then you pipe it through self-care, taking care of yourself.

00:03:05.419 --> 00:03:10.720
Then you found a core group, and then you make your group welcoming.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:13.119
So if you're a Python person, don't worry.

00:03:13.119 --> 00:03:19.399
I wrote it in Python syntax as well.

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:24.119
So let's talk about taking care of yourself.

00:03:24.119 --> 00:03:30.119
So really, all of these negative things in your head, you need to stop that.

00:03:30.119 --> 00:03:37.360
Because it's what prevents you from connecting with people and asking for help.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:39.160
So what instead?

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:42.399
So reframe all of those thoughts.

00:03:42.399 --> 00:03:44.800
It's not just you.

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:48.399
I just saw Barbie, so it is Knuff.

00:03:48.399 --> 00:03:52.320
And you are helping people.

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:55.479
But the thing to remember is that you come first.

00:03:55.479 --> 00:03:59.279
So I think one of those things is a lot of meetup organizers

00:03:59.279 --> 00:04:00.759
are people pleasers.

00:04:00.759 --> 00:04:05.000
And they want to send out doodle polls and make everyone happy,

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.199
finding the ideal time.

00:04:07.199 --> 00:04:08.520
You don't have to do that.

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:12.559
Make yourself happy, because especially if you're a volunteer,

00:04:12.559 --> 00:04:14.080
you're not getting paid.

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:18.239
You need to make it easier on yourself.

00:04:18.239 --> 00:04:22.040
So the other side of this, and I think this is the key to my talk.

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:24.119
I'll say that probably multiple times.

00:04:24.119 --> 00:04:29.480
But it's OK to not know everything and to admit your vulnerability.

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:36.679
Asking someone to help is really the core of establishing a community.

00:04:36.679 --> 00:04:38.839
So I am going to read this out loud, because I

00:04:38.839 --> 00:04:40.359
think it's just so important.

00:04:40.359 --> 00:04:42.040
So this is Adam Grant.

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:46.279
If you're familiar with him, he does a lot of talking about work

00:04:46.279 --> 00:04:49.920
and how we can make work not suck.

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:53.359
So he says, admitting that we have something to learn

00:04:53.359 --> 00:04:55.239
doesn't just show humility.

00:04:55.239 --> 00:04:58.200
It improves relationships.

00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:01.000
When we acknowledge that we don't know everything,

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.359
others feel more psychologically safe and become more effective.

00:05:05.359 --> 00:05:10.559
So expressing our desire to get better can help others get better.

00:05:10.559 --> 00:05:13.720
So really, the key I want you to remember

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:15.399
is that you're not alone.

00:05:15.399 --> 00:05:20.839
And this vulnerability is going to connect you with other people.

00:05:20.839 --> 00:05:23.519
So we talked about taking care of ourselves.

00:05:23.519 --> 00:05:27.000
So let's start talking about building a core group.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.760
And this was advice that just came from multiple organizers,

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:33.600
is to start small.

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:36.399
And we'll talk more about that in a little bit.

00:05:36.399 --> 00:05:39.279
So a core group, you share interests.

00:05:39.279 --> 00:05:40.839
We all like data.

00:05:40.839 --> 00:05:45.160
And some of us want to discuss it.

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:49.160
And part of the advice that I got from almost everyone

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:52.519
is don't organize alone.

00:05:52.519 --> 00:05:57.359
And part of the reason for that is when each other is feeling

00:05:57.359 --> 00:06:01.000
burned out, the others can help support them.

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:06.839
So how do you find this core group?

00:06:06.839 --> 00:06:10.480
And I just went through the Our Ladies organization guide.

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:12.519
They have a lot more advice on this.

00:06:12.519 --> 00:06:15.320
This is just my little bit of advice.

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:19.320
So I think it's really, it's a lot of people put out a call,

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:21.079
like if anyone wants to help.

00:06:21.079 --> 00:06:22.760
I think if you want to build a core group,

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:26.519
I think you should ask people directly.

00:06:26.519 --> 00:06:30.000
I think it's one of those things that forms a strong connection.

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:35.480
And people are really glad that you thought of them.

00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:37.839
So now you've established this core group.

00:06:37.839 --> 00:06:41.519
So let's talk about your values as a group.

00:06:41.519 --> 00:06:45.559
And so remember, we talked about vulnerability is important.

00:06:45.559 --> 00:06:47.880
Values are also important.

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:51.200
So us at Portland, our user group,

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:54.359
our values are we want to learn together.

00:06:54.359 --> 00:06:57.079
And that kind of informs everything that we do.

00:06:57.079 --> 00:06:58.799
But we also want to be fun.

00:06:58.799 --> 00:07:00.239
And we want to welcome beginners.

00:07:00.239 --> 00:07:04.480
So that also informs all of our communications.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:07.760
We try to make it as encouraging to beginners as possible.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:11.359
This is just a note.

00:07:11.359 --> 00:07:14.519
So I know a lot of you do internal meetups

00:07:14.519 --> 00:07:16.519
for an organization.

00:07:16.519 --> 00:07:18.559
So I just want to make a pitch that you

00:07:18.559 --> 00:07:23.160
ask your boss to give you some protected time.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:25.559
Because this is a lot of work.

00:07:25.559 --> 00:07:28.399
You're putting a lot of emotional effort.

00:07:28.399 --> 00:07:30.480
And you're connecting people.

00:07:30.480 --> 00:07:33.760
You need to get buy-in from the higher ups.

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:41.279
So I think I'm just kind of zooming through this talk.

00:07:41.279 --> 00:07:42.720
That's fine.

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:44.920
So let's talk about making your group welcoming.

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:47.559
And I also want to kind of end with some examples

00:07:47.559 --> 00:07:53.679
of activities that are kind of low risk and high reward.

00:07:53.679 --> 00:07:56.279
So you have your core group.

00:07:56.279 --> 00:07:58.880
And like almost everyone, I said,

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:03.079
that core group is going to grow either by word of mouth.

00:08:03.079 --> 00:08:09.559
And slowly, people are going to start joining your group.

00:08:09.559 --> 00:08:13.600
So one thing that I spent a lot of time kind of talking

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:18.000
and researching with people was, how do you make a group

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.920
psychologically safe for everyone?

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:25.799
And this is core to kind of welcoming people.

00:08:25.799 --> 00:08:29.559
So the formula I kind of came up with

00:08:29.559 --> 00:08:34.359
is, safety is values plus code of conduct.

00:08:34.359 --> 00:08:37.440
So there's been a lot written about code of conduct.

00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:41.479
And if you go to the website, there'll be a link later.

00:08:41.479 --> 00:08:45.320
There's going to be lots of links to codes of conduct

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:47.880
and how you should think about them.

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:51.000
So codes of conduct really address

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.119
kind of the unacceptable behavior.

00:08:54.119 --> 00:08:56.119
But I think the other side is that you

00:08:56.119 --> 00:08:58.559
have to encourage values.

00:08:58.559 --> 00:09:02.960
And because values are what kind of drive positive behavior.

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:05.200
So it's not just a code of conduct.

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:09.080
It's also making people feel like they're valued

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:11.159
and expressing those values.

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:18.119
So let's kind of end with activities.

00:09:18.119 --> 00:09:19.960
And I think one of the things that

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:23.640
will help alleviate burnout is making it easy for other people

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:24.880
to contribute.

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:30.719
And I loved Reva's example of making our ladies modular.

00:09:30.719 --> 00:09:36.320
Because I think all groups have people who want to help.

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:39.840
You just have to make the way for them.

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:46.239
So one of the easy, low-risk kind of activities,

00:09:46.239 --> 00:09:50.840
I think almost every organizer has done, is lightning talks.

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:54.159
So lightning talks are great.

00:09:54.159 --> 00:09:57.200
But I want to just kind of show this is something

00:09:57.200 --> 00:09:59.280
that we do at Portland, our user group.

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:02.719
And part of our goal is just to help each other.

00:10:02.719 --> 00:10:04.159
So we do this thing.

00:10:04.159 --> 00:10:05.960
This is kind of our default activity.

00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:07.599
And it's called aggregate.

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:12.280
And all of us kind of come in with issues or problems

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:14.799
we want to solve or something we want to share.

00:10:14.799 --> 00:10:21.520
And oftentimes, none of us, we don't know anything about it.

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:25.359
But collectively, we can figure things out.

00:10:25.359 --> 00:10:29.200
And I think that's one of the most fun things about Portland

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:33.320
R is that kind of collective knowledge

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:35.919
and sharing with each other.

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:38.039
So this is just an example.

00:10:38.039 --> 00:10:42.799
So what we do, it's a pretty low-key way

00:10:42.799 --> 00:10:45.760
to kind of organize a meetup.

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:50.559
We basically may have a short talk or demo.

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:54.840
But then we basically, you can see this intro section,

00:10:54.840 --> 00:10:57.559
we basically ask everyone to sign in

00:10:57.559 --> 00:11:00.119
with your name and background and what you want to learn

00:11:00.119 --> 00:11:02.479
and show today.

00:11:02.479 --> 00:11:06.440
So this is something that, and then we go down the list.

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:09.440
We try to hit as many people as possible.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:12.400
And we try to find answers.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:16.640
This is another activity that I've

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:21.159
done within Biodata Club, which is the idea of exploring data

00:11:21.159 --> 00:11:21.960
together.

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:24.400
So I call it a data scavenger hunt.

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:28.640
So this is a shiny app I developed

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:31.119
called Burrow that lets people kind of develop

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:35.679
these kind of basically exploratory data analysis.

00:11:35.679 --> 00:11:39.400
So this is a visualization by, oh, God.

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:41.719
I'm forgetting Nick's name.

00:11:41.719 --> 00:11:43.200
Sorry, Nick.

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:48.559
But this basically shows you information about the data,

00:11:48.559 --> 00:11:50.400
gives you an overview of the data.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:54.719
And these gray bars in each of these columns

00:11:54.719 --> 00:11:56.840
basically show missing data.

00:11:56.840 --> 00:11:59.200
So that's kind of the start of the conversation.

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:01.960
And then we start asking questions of the data,

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:06.320
like can we see relationships between different variables?

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:09.039
So something like age and blood pressure.

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:11.960
This app basically kind of gives you

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:15.400
the ability to kind of quickly kind of iterate through a data

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:19.159
set and find things like that.

00:12:19.159 --> 00:12:24.080
OK, so like I said, this is a pretty short talk.

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:28.679
But just revisiting the formula, so we talked about self-care.

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:30.679
We talked about having a core group

00:12:30.679 --> 00:12:32.559
and how that's so essential.

00:12:32.559 --> 00:12:39.000
And we talked about making our group welcoming.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:44.000
And hopefully by the end, but groups are organic

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.280
and they keep on growing.

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:46.960
But hopefully what we'll have in the end

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:50.400
is a sustainable community that supports each other

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:53.559
and we can avoid burnout.

00:12:53.559 --> 00:12:55.760
And this is one of the coolest things.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:59.280
I was talking with some organizers.

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:06.719
And the transition from just kind of stating your values

00:13:06.719 --> 00:13:10.280
to the values becoming the norms for the group.

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:13.280
And I think this is one of the most wonderful things

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:17.280
about doing community organizing.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:18.640
So thank you.

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:22.880
So these are all of the people I talked with.

00:13:22.880 --> 00:13:26.599
This is kind of an ongoing project for me.

00:13:26.599 --> 00:13:30.880
So I love to talk with any other data science organizers

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:34.039
and kind of get your perspectives.

00:13:34.039 --> 00:13:36.919
And on the right, basically, that's

00:13:36.919 --> 00:13:41.119
the core group for the Portland R Group.

00:13:41.119 --> 00:13:45.719
Just R Ladies Global, I've learned so much from them.

00:13:45.719 --> 00:13:48.559
But also R OpenSci and the Center

00:13:48.559 --> 00:13:52.520
for Scientific Collaboration and Community Engagement.

00:13:52.520 --> 00:13:54.960
So they actually offer courses in this.

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:56.559
Highly recommend.

00:13:56.559 --> 00:13:59.440
And also, this is my tribute to all of the organizers

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:01.039
because you do important work.

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:04.479
And I want you to know that.

00:14:04.479 --> 00:14:07.119
So join the conversation.

00:14:07.119 --> 00:14:10.479
So there is a community organizers channel

00:14:10.479 --> 00:14:12.719
in the Discord.

00:14:12.719 --> 00:14:16.119
You know, if you'd like to kind of introduce yourself,

00:14:16.119 --> 00:14:19.080
I'd love to talk with you.

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:21.479
So the website here, this is a QR code.

00:14:21.479 --> 00:14:26.640
But it's also at bit.ly slash meet dash burn.

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:29.280
And this is my information for connecting.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:30.520
And thank you very much.

00:14:40.520 --> 00:14:41.400
All right.

00:14:41.400 --> 00:14:42.119
Thank you, Ted.

00:14:42.119 --> 00:14:43.200
We've got a couple of minutes, which

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:44.760
is good because you've got a bunch of questions.

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:45.479
Oh, great.

00:14:45.479 --> 00:14:49.640
So first up, do you see burnout as more

00:14:49.640 --> 00:14:52.599
about a lack of connection or motivation

00:14:52.599 --> 00:14:56.679
or a loss of wellness more than simply overwork?

00:14:56.679 --> 00:14:58.000
Wow.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:14:58.919
That's a deep one.

00:15:01.760 --> 00:15:04.679
What I would say is that there are,

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:06.440
the thing I didn't talk about burnout

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:09.919
are the systemic elements, like culturally,

00:15:09.919 --> 00:15:13.719
like if you're in a group that prizes over work.

00:15:13.719 --> 00:15:17.239
But I think I would hedge my bets

00:15:17.239 --> 00:15:21.840
and say it's kind of both and including the systemic part.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:24.960
Hopefully that is a good answer.

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:26.960
It's a fantastic answer because it's your answer.

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:27.559
All right.

00:15:27.599 --> 00:15:30.640
Next up, how do you handle being an organizer

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:35.200
or becoming one if you are a serious introvert?

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:37.719
This is a really good one.

00:15:37.719 --> 00:15:41.760
I think part of it, and this is something

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:47.520
that I've learned over a lot of time, is kind of if you're

00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:51.159
an introvert, you're very good at inhabiting a role.

00:15:51.159 --> 00:15:54.479
And so kind of figuring out what that role is for yourself

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:57.880
is one of the ways that you can be very outgoing.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:00.640
To me, I kind of think of it like a mask or a costume

00:16:00.640 --> 00:16:02.039
or a uniform.

00:16:02.039 --> 00:16:06.000
And that helps me kind of reach out and interact with people.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.159
I think also just realizing that there's

00:16:10.159 --> 00:16:16.000
all of these dependencies and people

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.760
want to connect with each other is having

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:21.280
that kind of positive attitude.

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:25.719
But yeah, I have a lot to say about introversion.

00:16:25.719 --> 00:16:28.559
And it's taken me kind of a long time to even get to this point.

00:16:28.559 --> 00:16:30.280
But yeah.

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:32.559
So please, please reach out.

00:16:32.559 --> 00:16:34.559
And we can talk more about it.

00:16:34.559 --> 00:16:36.320
All right, shout out to all the introverts in the room.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:36.880
We see you.

